**Abstract:** Critical response (August 1, 1995) to James V. Schall's article "The Role of Christian Philosophy in Politics." Challenges Schall's claim that Christian philosophy provides universally valid ethical guidance demonstrable by reason alone. Argues that the distinction between faith and reason (traced to Aquinas) undermines Christian voice in pluralistic society. Uses abortion debate to illustrate how Christians may have resources unavailable to non-believers, calling for honest acknowledgment of different Christian perspectives rather than appeal to "neutral reason."
**AI Recommendation:** HIGH - Important application of Monasterio's theoretical critique to contemporary Catholic political ethics; demonstrates practical implications of his epistemological position.

